<br>
That is pretty much what I meant! I am considering the (Significant IMO) possibility that Sadham has carefully planned his defence to achieve neither a US defeat nor an Iraqi victory. Rather a military stalemate and a (humiliating) political climb down by the US.<br>
<br>
As long as Baghdad remains defended, A “Battle for Baghdad” would be calamitous! It isn’t going to happen (at least I hope it isn’t). Without a successful Battle for Baghdad the coalition can’t win!<br>
<br>
Of course (as things stand at present!) The coalition can’t lose either. There is no chance of Sadhams forces driving a vanquished coalition into the sea. But my point is that Sadham isn’t playing to “win” He is playing to “not-lose” and therefore survive (Star Trek fans out there, remember Data’s “Stratagema” match!)<br>
<br>
This is the traditional Arab fighting technique for centurys . When attacked they “bend like grass in the wind” and vanish into the desert only to come back at you when you least expect it. <br>
<br>
Sadham is unlikely to win any major battles outside Baghdad because of US air supremacy, but I fully expect him to take maximum advantage of the weather whenever it goes in his favour and aircraft are useless. Also AIUI laser sights don’t work too well in sandstorms. How good are US tankers at “Steam Gunnery?” I suspect Sadhams crack gunners are quite good; they’ve had lots of practice! And I would not be surprised if they were capable of inflicting significant damage.<br>
<br>
Sadham isn’t trying to win this militarily; he is trying to win it politically. The longer this drags on the more difficult the US position will become. If we are still outside Baghdad in two or three weeks with Sadham inside pulling faces at us I will be very concerned since other factors will begin to come into play.<br>
<br>
Allow me to explain<br>
<br>
ISTM that the overt aim of the US led attack was two fold (There are, I believe, other less well publicised, or even discussed, reasons  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :satansmoke --><img src=http://www.smilies-world.de/Smilies/Smilies_klein_1/sasmokin.gif ALT=":satansmoke"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->   but I’ll deal with them in another post!)<br>
<br>
1)To depose a vicious and evil dictator, perceived to be a danger to us and to liberate his people, and I do really believe that many US sincerely believe that! (I have seen comments from US Marines who are really quite upset about the resistance they are meeting and cannot comprehend why the Iraqi people seem so reluctant to be liberated)<br>
<br>
2) To intimidate the other members of the “Axis-of-Terror” by performing the attack with overwhelming force and achieving a swift victory. “Shock and Awe”!<br>
<br>
I’m sorry guys, but after 12 days, you just don’t look shocking, awesome or intimidating any more!!<br>
<br>
And that is dangerous.<br>
<br>
President Bush has, IMO, made a serious blunder by, more or less, publicly stating that Iran is next on the list. Telling the whole world where your next war is going to be before finishing this one *and* forewarning your future enemy at the same time seems to me to be a not terribly good strategy!<br>
<br>
Rumsfeld has compounded this *in spades* by rattling his sabres over the weekend at Syria, Iran and even N Korea! <br>
<br>
I’ll bet Iran and N Korea are working their little socks off on their respective nuclear programs!<br>
<br>
Any bets on a N Korean nuclear test in the next couple of weeks or so? Possibly followed by an invasion of the South? <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :tnt --><img src=http://www.smilies-world.de/Smilies/Smilies_boese_1/blowingup.gif ALT=":tnt"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <br>
<br>
With the bulk of the US Army bogged down indefinitely in southern Iraq, Kim Jong II must realise that there will be <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><span style="text-decoration:underline"><!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>no-better-time</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--></span><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> to fight the war with America that now seems inevitable.<br>
<br>
